# Fluff Date: 2026-03-11 21:02:11
<overview>
<p>The T-12 Tiger emerged from House Davion's search for a conventional armored platform capable of meeting the threats posed by the BattleMech revolution of the Age of War. While most successor powers poured resources into fusion-powered walkers, Veridian Dynamics on Torrence delivered a tracked medium tank that matched or exceeded contemporary designs at a fraction of the cost. Introduced in 2478, the Tiger quickly became the primary main battle tank of the Armed Forces of the Federated Suns and spread to dozens of other militaries across the Inner Sphere and Periphery over the following decades. Its influence on armored warfare doctrine during the Age of War and Reunification War period established the Tiger as one of the most widely produced and operated conventional vehicles of its era.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Tiger's primary weapon is the Federated Autoloader/10-B medium autocannon, a heavy-caliber system capable of defeating the armor of most contemporary combat vehicles while maintaining a high rate of fire. Two tons of ammunition allow for sustained engagement, though most crews carry standard armor-piercing rounds given the single ton available for the SRM pack. The autocannon's proven design and low maintenance requirements contributed significantly to the Tiger's appeal for mass production.</p><p>Supplementing the main gun, a Grizzly-3 Minigun mounts coaxially, providing effective anti-infantry fire in close-quarters engagements. An Archer SRM-4 Pack adds medium-range punch against armored targets, while two Borman-A5C Heavy Machineguns protect the fore and aft quarters from infantry assault. This combined armament package gives the Tiger credible capability against all target types encountered in combined-arms operations.</p><p>The Tiger's principal weakness is its protection. The Quantum Heavy Plate covers barely ten percent of the vehicle's total mass, sufficient to absorb hits from its own autocannon on most facings but vulnerable to heavier weapons systems common among contemporary BattleMechs and larger vehicles. The Veridian 220 ICE delivers reliable performance at a top speed of 64 kph, adequate for most tactical roles but insufficient to disengage from faster opponents once contact is made.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The T-12 served as the primary main battle tank for the Armed Forces of the Federated Suns throughout the Age of War and Reunification War, deployed in armored regiments and combined-arms formations across Davion space. Its low production cost allowed widespread fielding in both garrison and line units. As licenses spread to Lyran, Capellan, Combine, and Free Worlds League facilities, Tiger variants entered service across much of the Inner Sphere and Periphery. Reserve and militia forces continued operating the design for generations after front-line units transitioned to newer equipment.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Veridian Dynamics developed the Tiger in response to House Davion's directive to field a capable main battle tank that could be produced quickly and economically across multiple facilities. The Armed Forces of the Federated Suns adopted the T-12 before the close of the Age of War, relying on it as the backbone of their armored forces through the Reunification Wars. The design's simplicity and substantially lower cost compared to fusion-powered alternatives made it equally attractive to other powers, and production licenses spread rapidly during the late 25th century.</p><p>The political alliance between the Federated Suns and the Lyran Commonwealth brought the Tiger to Lyran production lines in the 2480s, with Veridian's facility on Tamar among the first to operate under that arrangement. By the early 26th century, virtually every industrialized power in the Inner Sphere was operating some version of the Tiger. Licensed production appeared in the Capellan Confederation, the Draconis Combine, and the Free Worlds League, while facilities in the Deep Periphery, including Bordello Military Goods on Antwerp, produced the design for Hanseatic League forces and continued doing so well into the ilClan era.</p><p>The Tiger was showing its age by the Reunification War. Heavier and better-protected designs had emerged across the Inner Sphere, and the AFFS phased the T-12 out of front-line service before the war concluded. Several powers briefly restarted production during the early Succession Wars to offset equipment losses, taking advantage of the design's mature manufacturing base. No major production lines remained active by the nadir of the Succession Wars, and the Tiger survived mainly in reserve formations, planetary militias, and the occasional mercenary unit.</p><p>During the Davion Civil War, Colonel John Gordon of the First Avalon Dragoons served as one of Alexander Davion's principal field commanders, directing actions across dozens of Capellan March and Crucis worlds from the cupola of a modified Tiger. Gordon's capture and subsequent execution on Jaipur marked one of the civil war's most costly losses for the Davionist cause.</p>
</history>

